# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: statistical-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:statistical-charts/bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In descriptive statistics, a **box plot** or **boxplot** is a method for demonstrating graphically the locality, spread and skewness groups of numerical data through their quartiles.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In addition to the box on a box plot, there can be lines (which are called *whiskers*) extending from the box indicating variability outside the upper and lower quartiles, thus, the plot is also called the **box-and-whisker plot** and the **box-and-whisker diagram**.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Outliers that differ significantly from the rest of the dataset may be plotted as individual points beyond the whiskers on the box plot.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Box plots are non-parametric: they display variation in samples of a statistical population without making any assumptions of the underlying statistical distribution (though Tukey's box plot assumes symmetry for the whiskers and normality for their length).
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The spacings in each subsection of the box plot indicate the degree of dispersion (spread) and skewness of the data, which are usually described using the five-number summary.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In addition, the box plot allows one to visually estimate various L-estimators, notably the interquartile range, midhinge, range, mid-range, and trimean.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Box plots can be drawn either horizontally or vertically.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The range-bar method was first introduced by Mary Eleanor Spear in her book "Charting Statistics" in 1952 and again in her book "Practical Charting Techniques" in 1969.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The box-and-whisker plot was first introduced in 1970 by John Tukey, who later published on the subject in his book "Exploratory Data Analysis" in 1977.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] A box plot is a standardized way of displaying the dataset based on the five-number summary: the minimum, the maximum, the sample median, and the first and third quartiles.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The box is drawn from *Q*1 to *Q*3 with a horizontal line drawn inside it to denote the median.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Some box plots include an additional character to represent the mean of the data.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The whiskers must end at an observed data point, but can be defined in various ways.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In the most straightforward method, the boundary of the lower whisker is the minimum value of the data set, and the boundary of the upper whisker is the maximum value of the data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Because of this variability, it is appropriate to describe the convention that is being used for the whiskers and outliers in the caption of the box plot.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Another popular choice for the boundaries of the whiskers is based on the 1.5 IQR value.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] From above the upper quartile (***Q*3**), a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out and a whisker is drawn *up to* the largest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Similarly, a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out below the lower quartile (***Q*1**) and a whisker is drawn *down to* the lowest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Because the whiskers must end at an observed data point, the whisker lengths can look unequal, even though 1.5 IQR is the same for both sides.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] All other observed data points outside the boundary of the whiskers are plotted as **outliers**.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The outliers can be plotted on the box plot as a dot, a small circle, a star, *etc.* (see example below).
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Rarely, box plot can be plotted without the whiskers.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] This can be appropriate for sensitive information to avoid whiskers (and outliers) disclosing actual values observed.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The unusual percentiles 2%, 9%, 91%, 98% are sometimes used for whisker cross-hatches and whisker ends to depict the seven-number summary.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] If the data are normally distributed, the locations of the seven marks on the box plot will be equally spaced.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] On some box plots, a cross-hatch is placed before the end of each whisker.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Tukey first popularized this type of visual data display in 1969, several variations on the classical box plot have been developed, and the two most commonly found variations are the variable-width box plots and the notched box plots.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] One convention for obtaining the boundaries of these notches is to use a distance of $\pm {\frac {1.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}$ around the median.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] For a symmetrical data distribution, the medcouple will be zero, and this reduces the adjusted box plot to the Tukey's box plot with equal whisker lengths of $1.5{\text{ IQR}}$ for both whiskers.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] A series of hourly temperatures were measured throughout the day in degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] A box plot of the data set can be generated by first calculating five relevant values of this data set: minimum, maximum, median (***Q*2**), first quartile (***Q*1**), and third quartile (***Q*3**).
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The minimum is the smallest number of the data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In this case, the minimum recorded day temperature is 57°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The maximum is the largest number of the data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In this case, the maximum recorded day temperature is 81°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The median is the "middle" number of the ordered data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] This means that exactly 50% of the elements are below the median and 50% of the elements are greater than the median.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The median of this ordered data set is 70°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The first quartile value (***Q*1** **or 25th percentile)** is the number that marks one quarter of the ordered data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 25% of the elements that are less than the first quartile and exactly 75% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The first quartile value can be easily determined by finding the "middle" number between the minimum and the median.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number found between 57°F and 70°F is 66°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The third quartile value (***Q*3** **or 75th percentile)** is the number that marks three quarters of the ordered data set.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 75% of the elements that are less than the third quartile and 25% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The third quartile value can be easily obtained by finding the "middle" number between the median and the maximum.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number between 70°F and 81°F is 75°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The upper whisker boundary of the box plot is the largest data value that is within 1.5 IQR above the third quartile.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F and the maximum is 81°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the value of the maximum, which is 81°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Similarly, the lower whisker boundary of the box plot is the smallest data value that is within 1.5 IQR below the first quartile.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F and the minimum is 57°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the value of the minimum, which is 57°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In this example, only the first and the last number are changed.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The median, third quartile, and first quartile remain the same.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] In this case, the maximum value in this data set is 89°F, and 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The maximum is greater than 1.5 IQR plus the third quartile, so the maximum is an outlier.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the greatest value smaller than 1.5 IQR above the third quartile, which is 79°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Similarly, the minimum value in this data set is 52°F, and 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] The minimum is smaller than 1.5 IQR minus the first quartile, so the minimum is also an outlier.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the smallest value greater than 1.5 IQR below the first quartile, which is 57°F.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Using the above example that has 24 data points (*n* = 24), one can calculate the median, first and third quartile either mathematically or visually.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Although box plots may seem more primitive than histograms or kernel density estimates, they do have a number of advantages.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] First, the box plot enables statisticians to do a quick graphical examination on one or more data sets.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Box plots also take up less space and are therefore particularly useful for comparing distributions between several groups or sets of data in parallel.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Lastly, the overall structure of histograms and kernel density estimate can be strongly influenced by the choice of number and width of bins techniques and the choice of bandwidth, respectively.
[src:statistical-charts/box-plot] Although looking at a statistical distribution is more common than looking at a box plot, it can be useful to compare the box plot against the probability density function (theoretical histogram) for a normal N(0,*σ*2) distribution and observe their characteristics directly.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] A **histogram** is a visual representation of the distribution of quantitative data.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] To construct a histogram, the first step is to "bin" (or "bucket") the range of values— divide the entire range of values into a series of intervals—and then count how many values fall into each interval.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The bins are usually specified as consecutive, non-overlapping intervals of a variable.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The bins (intervals) are adjacent and are typically (but not required to be) of equal size.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Histograms give a rough sense of the density of the underlying distribution of the data, and often for density estimation: estimating the probability density function of the underlying variable.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The total area of a histogram used for probability density is always normalized to 1.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] If the length of the intervals on the *x*-axis are all 1, then a histogram is identical to a relative frequency plot.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Histograms are sometimes confused with bar charts.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] In a histogram, each bin is for a different range of values, so altogether the histogram illustrates the distribution of values.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] But in a bar chart, each bar is for a different category of observations (e.g., each bar might be for a different population), so altogether the bar chart can be used to compare different categories.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Some authors recommend that bar charts always have gaps between the bars to clarify that they are not histograms.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The term *histogram* was first introduced by Karl Pearson, the founder of mathematical statistics, in lectures delivered in 1892 at University College London.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Pearson's term is sometimes incorrectly said to combine the Greek root γραμμα (*gramma*; 'figure' or 'drawing') with the root ἱστορία (historia; 'inquiry or 'history').
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Alternatively the root ἱστίον (*histion*) is also proposed, meaning 'web' or 'tissue' (as in histology, the study of biological tissue).
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Both of these etymologies are incorrect, and in fact Pearson, who knew Ancient Greek well, derived the term from a different if homophonous Greek root, ἱστός ('something set upright' or 'mast'), referring to the vertical bars in the graph.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Pearson's new term was embedded in a series of other analogous neologisms, such as *stigmogram* and *radiogram*.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Pearson himself noted in 1895 that, although the term *histogram* was new, the type of graph it designates was "a common form of graphical representation".
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] In fact the technique of using a bar graph to represent statistical measurements was devised by the Scottish economist, William Playfair, in his *Commercial and political atlas* (1786).
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The words used to describe the patterns in a histogram are: "symmetric", "skewed left" or "right", "unimodal", "bimodal" or "multimodal".
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] It is a good idea to plot the data using several different bin widths to learn more about it.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Here is an example on tips given in a restaurant.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Census Bureau found that there were 124 million people who work outside of their homes.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Using their data on the time occupied by travel to work, the table below shows the absolute number of people who responded with travel times "at least 30 but less than 35 minutes" is higher than the numbers for the categories above and below it.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This is likely due to people rounding their reported journey time.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The problem of reporting values as somewhat arbitrarily rounded numbers is a common phenomenon when collecting data from people.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This histogram shows the number of cases per unit interval as the height of each block, so that the area of each block is equal to the number of people in the survey who fall into its category.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The area under the curve represents the total number of cases (124 million).
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This type of histogram shows absolute numbers, with Q in thousands.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This histogram differs from the first only in the vertical scale.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The area of each block is the fraction of the total that each category represents, and the total area of all the bars is equal to 1 (the fraction meaning "all").
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The curve displayed is a simple density estimate.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This version shows proportions, and is also known as a unit area histogram.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] In other words, a histogram represents a frequency distribution by means of rectangles whose widths represent class intervals and whose areas are proportional to the corresponding frequencies: the height of each is the average frequency density for the interval.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The intervals are placed together in order to show that the data represented by the histogram, while exclusive, is also contiguous.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] (E.g., in a histogram it is possible to have two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 20.5–33.5, but not two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 22.5–32.5.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The data used to construct a histogram are generated via a function *m**i* that counts the number of observations that fall into each of the disjoint categories (known as *bins*).
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] A histogram can be thought of as a simplistic kernel density estimation, which uses a kernel to smooth frequencies over the bins.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This yields a smoother probability density function, which will in general more accurately reflect distribution of the underlying variable.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The density estimate could be plotted as an alternative to the histogram, and is usually drawn as a curve rather than a set of boxes.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Histograms are nevertheless preferred in applications, when their statistical properties need to be modeled.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The correlated variation of a kernel density estimate is very difficult to describe mathematically, while it is simple for a histogram where each bin varies independently.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] An alternative to kernel density estimation is the average shifted histogram, which is fast to compute and gives a smooth curve estimate of the density without using kernels.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] A cumulative histogram: a mapping that counts the cumulative number of observations in all of the bins up to the specified bin.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] There is no "best" number of bins, and different bin sizes can reveal different features of the data.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Grouping data is at least as old as Graunt's work in the 17th century, but no systematic guidelines were given until Sturges's work in 1926.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Using wider bins where the density of the underlying data points is low reduces noise due to sampling randomness; using narrower bins where the density is high (so the signal drowns the noise) gives greater precision to the density estimation.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Thus varying the bin-width within a histogram can be beneficial.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Nonetheless, equal-width bins are widely used.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Some theoreticians have attempted to determine an optimal number of bins, but these methods generally make strong assumptions about the shape of the distribution.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Depending on the actual data distribution and the goals of the analysis, different bin widths may be appropriate, so experimentation is usually needed to determine an appropriate width.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] There are, however, various useful guidelines and rules of thumb.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The braces indicate the ceiling function.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] which takes the square root of the number of data points in the sample and rounds to the next integer.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This rule is suggested by a number of elementary statistics textbooks and widely implemented in many software packages.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Sturges's rule is derived from a binomial distribution and implicitly assumes an approximately normal distribution.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Sturges's formula implicitly bases bin sizes on the range of the data, and can perform poorly if *n* < 30, because the number of bins will be small—less than seven—and unlikely to show trends in the data well.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] On the other extreme, Sturges's formula may overestimate bin width for very large datasets, resulting in oversmoothed histograms.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] It may also perform poorly if the data are not normally distributed.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] When compared to Scott's rule and the Terrell-Scott rule, two other widely accepted formulas for histogram bins, the output of Sturges's formula is closest when *n* ≈ 100.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The Rice rule is presented as a simple alternative to Sturges's rule.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Doane's formula is a modification of Sturges's formula which attempts to improve its performance with non-normal data.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] where ${\hat {\sigma }}$ is the sample standard deviation.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Scott's normal reference rule is optimal for random samples of normally distributed data, in the sense that it minimizes the integrated mean squared error of the density estimate.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This is the default rule used in Microsoft Excel.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The Terrell–Scott rule is not a normal reference rule.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] It gives the minimum number of bins required for an asymptotically optimal histogram, where optimality is measured by the integrated mean squared error.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The bound is derived by finding the 'smoothest' possible density, which turns out to be ${\frac {3}{4}}(1-x^{2})$ .
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Any other density will require more bins, hence the above estimate is also referred to as the 'oversmoothed' rule.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The similarity of the formulas and the fact that Terrell and Scott were at Rice University when the proposed it suggests that this is also the origin of the Rice rule.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] which is based on the interquartile range, denoted by IQR.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] It replaces 3.5σ of Scott's rule with 2 IQR, which is less sensitive than the standard deviation to outliers in data.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Here, $N_{k}$ is the number of datapoints in the *k*th bin, and choosing the value of *h* that minimizes *J* will minimize integrated mean squared error.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Rather than choosing evenly spaced bins, for some applications it is preferable to vary the bin width.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] A common case is to choose *equiprobable bins*, where the number of samples in each bin is expected to be approximately equal.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] The bins may be chosen according to some known distribution or may be chosen based on the data so that each bin has $\approx n/k$ samples.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] When plotting the histogram, the *frequency density* is used for the dependent axis.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] While all bins have approximately equal area, the heights of the histogram approximate the density distribution.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This choice of bins is motivated by maximizing the power of a Pearson chi-squared test testing whether the bins do contain equal numbers of samples.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Where $\Phi ^{-1}$ is the probit function.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Following this rule for $\alpha =0.05$ would give between $1.88n^{2/5}$ and $3.77n^{2/5}$ ; the coefficient of 2 is chosen as an easy-to-remember value from this broad optimum.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] A good reason why the number of bins should be proportional to ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ is the following: suppose that the data are obtained as n independent realizations of a bounded probability distribution with smooth density.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Then the histogram remains equally "rugged" as n tends to infinity.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] If s is the "width" of the distribution (e. g., the standard deviation or the inter-quartile range), then the number of units in a bin (the frequency) is of order $nh/s$ and the *relative* standard error is of order ${\sqrt {s/(nh)}}$ .
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] Compared to the next bin, the relative change of the frequency is of order $h/s$ provided that the derivative of the density is non-zero.
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] These two are of the same order if h is of order $s/{\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ , so that k is of order ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ .
[src:statistical-charts/histogram] This simple cubic root choice can also be applied to bins with non-constant widths.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A **scatter plot**, also called a **scatterplot**, **scatter graph**, **scatter chart**, **scattergram**, or **scatter diagram**, is a type of plot or mathematical diagram using Cartesian coordinates to display values for typically two variables for a set of data.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] If the points are coded (color/shape/size), one additional variable can be displayed.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The data are displayed as a collection of points, each having the value of one variable determining the position on the horizontal axis and the value of the other variable determining the position on the vertical axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The scatter diagram is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] According to Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis, the defining characteristic distinguishing scatter plots from line charts is the representation of specific observations of bivariate data where one variable is plotted on the horizontal axis and the other on the vertical axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The two variables are often abstracted from a physical representation like the spread of bullets on a target or a geographic or celestial projection.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] While Edmund Halley created a bivariate plot of temperature and pressure in 1686, he omitted the specific data points used to demonstrate the relationship.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Friendly and Denis claim his visualization was different from an actual scatter plot.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Friendly and Denis attribute the first scatter plot to John Herschel.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] In 1833, Herschel plotted the angle between the central star in the constellation Virgo and Gamma Virginis over time to find how the angle changes over time, not through calculation but with freehand drawing and human judgment.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Sir Francis Galton extended and popularized the scatter plot and many other statistical tools to pursue a scientific basis for eugenics.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] When, in 1886, Galton published a scatter plot and correlation ellipse of the height of parents and children, he extended Herschel's mere plotting of data points by binning and averaging adjacent cells to create a smoother visualization.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Fischer, and other statisticians and eugenicists built on Galton's work and formalized correlations and significance testing.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A scatter plot can be used either when one continuous variable is under the control of the experimenter and the other depends on it or when both continuous variables are independent.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] If a parameter exists that is systematically incremented and/or decremented by the other, it is called the *control parameter* or independent variable and is customarily plotted along the horizontal axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The measured or dependent variable is customarily plotted along the vertical axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] If no dependent variable exists, either type of variable can be plotted on either axis and a scatter plot will illustrate only the degree of correlation (not causation) between two variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A scatter plot can suggest various kinds of correlations between variables with a certain confidence interval.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] For example, weight and height would be on the y-axis, and height would be on the x-axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Correlations may be positive (rising), negative (falling), or null (uncorrelated).
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] If the dots' pattern slopes from lower left to upper right, it indicates a positive correlation between the variables being studied.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] If the pattern of dots slopes from upper left to lower right, it indicates a negative correlation.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A line of best fit (alternatively called 'trendline') can be drawn to study the relationship between the variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] An equation for the correlation between the variables can be determined by established best-fit procedures.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] For a linear correlation, the best-fit procedure is known as linear regression and is guaranteed to generate a correct solution in a finite time.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] No universal best-fit procedure is guaranteed to generate a correct solution for arbitrary relationships.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A scatter plot is also very useful when we wish to see how two comparable data sets agree to show nonlinear relationships between variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The ability to do this can be enhanced by adding a smooth line such as LOESS.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Furthermore, if the data are represented by a mixture model of simple relationships, these relationships will be visually evident as superimposed patterns.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Scatter charts can be built in the form of bubble, marker, or/and line charts.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] For example, to display a link between a person's lung capacity, and how long that person could hold their breath, a researcher would choose a group of people to study, then measure each one's lung capacity (first variable) and how long that person could hold their breath (second variable).
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The researcher would then plot the data in a scatter plot, assigning "lung capacity" to the horizontal axis, and "time holding breath" to the vertical axis.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A person with a lung capacity of 400 cl who held their breath for 21.7 s would be represented by a single dot on the scatter plot at the point (400, 21.7) in the Cartesian coordinates.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] The scatter plot of all the people in the study would enable the researcher to obtain a visual comparison of the two variables in the data set and will help to determine what kind of relationship there might be between the two variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] For a set of data variables (dimensions) *X*1, *X*2, ... , *X**k*, the scatter plot matrix shows all the pairwise scatter plots of the variables on a single view with multiple scatterplots in a matrix format.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] For k variables, the scatterplot matrix will contain k rows and k columns.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A plot located on the intersection of ith row and jth column is a plot of variables *X**i* versus *X**j*.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] This means that each row and column is one dimension, and each cell plots a scatter plot of two dimensions.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A **generalized scatter plot matrix** offers a range of displays of paired combinations of categorical and quantitative variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] A mosaic plot, fluctuation diagram, or faceted bar chart may be used to display two categorical variables.
[src:statistical-charts/scatter-plot] Other plots are used for one categorical and one quantitative variables.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:statistical-charts/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] A **violin plot** (also known as a **bean plot**) is a statistical graphic for comparing probability distributions.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] It is similar to a box plot, but has enhanced information with the addition of a rotated kernel density plot on each side.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The violin plot was proposed in 1997 by Jerry L.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] Nelson as a way to display even more information than box plots, which were created by John Tukey in 1977.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The name comes from the plot's alleged resemblance to a violin.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] Violin plots are similar to box plots, except that they also show the probability density of the data at different values, usually smoothed by a kernel density estimator.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] A violin plot will include all the data that is in a box plot: a marker for the median of the data; a box or marker indicating the interquartile range; and possibly all sample points, if the number of samples is not too high.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] While a box plot shows a summary statistics such as median and interquartile ranges, the violin plot shows the full distribution of the data.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The violin plot can be used in multimodal data (more than one peak).
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] In this case a violin plot shows the presence of different peaks, their position and relative amplitude.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] Like box plots, violin plots are used to represent comparison of a variable distribution (or sample distribution) across different "categories" (for example, temperature distribution compared between day and night, or distribution of car prices compared across different car makers).
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] For instance, the outer shape represents all possible results.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The next layer inside might represent the values that occur 95% of the time.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The next layer (if it exists) inside might represent the values that occur 50% of the time.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] Violin plots are less popular than box plots.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] Violin plots may be harder to understand for readers not familiar with them.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] In this case, a more accessible alternative is to plot a series of stacked histograms or kernel density plots.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] The original meaning of "violin plot" was a combination of a box plot and a two-sided kernel density plot.
[src:statistical-charts/violin-plot] However, currently "violin plots" are sometimes understood just as two-sided kernel density plots, without a box plot or any other elements.
